metadata.name: Circumscript #199
metadata.description:
It has always been a goal of mine to incorporate the worlds of physical and digital art together in a piece. And with circumscript I am the closest I've ever been. Circumscript uses a custom shader written to mix and "dilute" the colors on the canvas, thus creating a very physical feeling piece.

This dilution can be more or less depending on the edition, but always plays a huge role in the feel of the piece.


Happy new year.


----


[m] or [double tap] : opens the export/settings menu, use this menu to change the resolution, and make sure to press the reload button if you do.
[holding down] : zooms in on a certain area of the piece, depending on where your mouse/finger is. Use this feature to expore the complex textures of the piece in more detail, it's highly recommended to do this on a higher resolution setting.

The outputs can vary slighty per device, as there's a slight difference in how certain math gets interpreted on different devices with shaders.


----


Made with p5.js and webgl by Wouter Missler in 2022/3.

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #38
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #208
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: ASSEMBLING MACHINE #31
metadata.description:
The machine never sleeps.
Build. Construct. Develop. Create. Form. Produce. Generate. Repeat.
---------------
Collectors at the highest tier (125 tez) may claim a signed 8”x10” print of their mint. Please look for details about prints on Twitter (@teaboswell), or contact me directly
---------------
CONTROLS:
A - Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)
S - Download image
Double tap (mobile) - Download image
1-6 - Modify scale (1 = default, 2048 x 2730px, 6 = maximum, 12288 x 16380px (very performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F - Fit to current screen size
G - Toggle grain overlay
L - Toggle background grid lines
B - Cycle border sizes (0 -> 100 -> 200 -> 300px)

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: Gribouillis #20
metadata.description:
"Gribouillis" tends to reproduce the result of what you could draw without too much thinking on your sketchbook; an automatic drawing while listening to a call or podcast... Or something you would draw on the napkin of a restaurant without a strong focus...
Those kind of drawing that don't have a lot of meaning, but that, sometimes, give you find some comfort.

---

This is a "screenshot" of the current researches and work I'm doing to emulate a sensation of sketching.

---

Open the link and add '#hd' in the URL to have a A3 size of the artwork.

---

Made to run in browser, especially Chrome.
Works on most recent iPhones.

---

metadata.name: M-tore #76
metadata.description: This token generates abstract art using a recursive algorithm for rectangle splitting. The number of rectangles can be anywhere from 32 to 16384. There are several different strategies for splitting, each one producing distinctive results. The background can be dark or light. Color palettes are generated programmatically in eight different ways (e.g. monochromatic, complementary, analogous, etc.). Textures and effects are also generated programmatically using Perlin noise and pixel manipulation. To add dynamics, there is a probability of having some uncertainty in drawing rectangles, dots, and lines.

metadata.name: Bardez #126
metadata.description:
Bardez is the Armenian word for garden. It is etymologically tied to an ancient word for paradise, but that link goes deeper than etymology. Gardens have always been small pieces of paradise for me, and hearing the word in Armenian triggers a flood of warm memories.

Memories of wandering around my grandfather’s garden, plucking ripe plums and figs from their branches.
Memories of playing in my parents yard, the scent of jasmine in the summer heat.
Of sun warmed tomatoes in my mom’s vegetable patch.
The smell of dirt and grass.
Mud on my hands.
Sun on my skin.
Memories of paradise.

I hope you enjoy these gardens I’ve planted, and I hope they remind you of some warm and wonderful memories.
 
Nat Sarkissian






Notes:
 - This piece uses a shader to compute the lighting of the terrain in the first frame. If you don’t have a graphics card, you may have difficulty running this.

 - Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you the progress of the render, and also show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

 - Finally, collectors at the highest tier will be entitled to a signed print of their edition. For further details and updates, keep an eye on my Twitter (@_NatSarkissian).
